  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the top 10 books one must read before turning 20 something?",
  "response": "Here are ten influential and thought-provoking books often recommended for young readers before they turn 20:\n\n1. **\"To Kill a Mockingbird\" by Harper Lee**\n   - A powerful exploration of race, class, and morality in the American South, seen through the eyes of a child.\n\n2. **\"The Catcher in the Rye\" by J.D. Salinger**\n   - A classic coming-of-age novel that delves into themes of identity, alienation, and the challenges of adolescence.\n\n3. **\"1984\" by George Orwell**\n   - A dystopian novel that explores themes of totalitarianism, surveillance, and individuality, prompting critical thinking about power and freedom.\n\n4. **\"The Great Gatsby\" by F. Scott Fitzgerald**\n   - A tale of ambition, love, and the American Dream set in the 1920s that examines the consequences of wealth and social status.\n\n5. **\"Pride and Prejudice\" by Jane Austen**\n   - A romantic novel that also critiques the societal norms of the early 19th century, exploring themes of love, class, and personal growth.\n\n6. **\"The Alchemist\" by Paulo Coelho**\n   - A philosophical novel about pursuing one\u2019s dreams and finding one\u2019s personal legend through a journey of self-discovery.\n\n7. **\"The Diary of a Young Girl\" by Anne Frank**\n   - A poignant account of a young Jewish girl in hiding during World War II, illuminating the human spirit in the face of adversity.\n\n8. **\"Brave New World\" by Aldous Huxley**\n   - A thought-provoking dystopian novel that explores the implications of technological advancements and a society driven by consumerism.\n\n9. **\"The Perks of Being a Wallflower\" by Stephen Chbosky**\n   - A contemporary coming-of-age novel that addresses issues of mental health, friendship, and self-exploration during adolescence.\n\n10. **\"Fahrenheit 451\" by Ray Bradbury**\n    - A cautionary tale about a future society where books are banned, prompting discussions about censorship, knowledge, and conformity.\n\nThese books collectively offer insights into society, human nature, and the journey of growing up, making them valuable reads for anyone approaching their twenties.",
